📘 How to Analyze the Complexity of Recurrence Relations
📌 What is a Recurrence Relation?

A recurrence relation is an equation that shows the running time of a recursive algorithm.

It expresses the current problem in terms of smaller subproblems.

General Form
T(n) = Recursive Work + Extra Work
Example
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n)

This means:

Problem is divided into 2 smaller parts
Each part has size n/2
Merging both parts takes O(n) time

Example: Merge Sort

🎯 Why Do We Solve Recurrence Relations?

Solving recurrence relations helps us:

Find the time complexity of recursive algorithms.
Compare algorithm efficiency.
Choose the best algorithm.
Understand how recursion grows.
Optimize recursive solutions.
🧠 Steps to Analyze a Recursive Algorithm
Step 1: Count Recursive Calls

Find how many recursive calls are made.

Example:

fun(n/2);
fun(n/2);

There are 2 recursive calls.

Step 2: Find Problem Size

Check how the input size changes.

Example

n → n/2
Step 3: Find Extra Work

Look for loops or other operations outside recursion.

Example

for(int i=0;i<n;i++)

Extra work = O(n)

Step 4: Write the Recurrence

Combine everything.

T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n)
🔥 Methods to Solve Recurrence Relations

There are 3 popular methods.

1️⃣ Substitution Method
Idea
Guess the answer.
Prove it using Mathematical Induction.
Best For
Small recurrence relations.
When you already know the expected complexity.
Example
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n

Guess:

T(n) = O(n log n)

Then prove it.

2️⃣ Recursion Tree Method
Idea

Draw recursion as a tree.

Calculate:

Cost of each level
Number of levels

Finally,

Total Cost = Sum of all levels
Example
        T(n)
      /      \
   T(n/2)   T(n/2)

If every level costs n

and there are log n levels,

Then

Time Complexity = O(n log n)
3️⃣ Master Theorem

The fastest method for Divide & Conquer recurrences.

It works only for:

T(n) = aT(n/b) + f(n)

Where

a = Number of recursive calls
b = Size reduction factor
f(n) = Extra work

Example

T(n)=2T(n/2)+n

Answer

O(n log n)
📌 Common Examples
Recurrence	Algorithm	Complexity
T(n)=T(n/2)+1	Binary Search	O(log n)
T(n)=2T(n/2)+n	Merge Sort	O(n log n)
T(n)=T(n-1)+1	Linear Recursion	O(n)
T(n)=T(n-1)+n	Recursive Sum	O(n²)
